UPDATE(14/02/2025):

Hello. So it has been some time since I have updated this: and now seems the right time with resent revelations(yes those ones) to give a little more light to this subject from my perspective. 
Specifically about browsers and the role of keeping anonymous online (should you wish too) in 2026. Firstly the "should you wish too" explained: 
there are benefit's to being semi-anonymous on the internet and that is great, people don't know whom you are: odd stalker's can't find you as easily. 
Which in today's world where there are A.I tool's that can find you on a map from a simple picture(search engine it), within seconds. That has implications 
that can be a great deal more depending on the context of your security model/needs. And that is mostly the point I'm trying to make is that is is about your 
threat model.

OK yes undoubtedly there are some benefit's to not putting your entire life online, you can just avoid it: but do you want to?
that's the question everyone has to ask themselves but it is hard to answer without some knowledge of how it works. Sure it's easy to do 
the whole pseudo anonymous thing to a degree(use a VPN, never post personally indefinable pictures, strip said pictures of metadata and 
use an animated picture or something of a kind). But what about platforms like "X"?  You need a credit card or some payment system to be verified. 
So even if I strip my pictures of meta data so you can't get the GPS location of where some picture was taken and it has no landmarks in it 
so you can't use A.I tools so easily: the person that owns X still clearly knows whom you or I am; furthermore am I limiting myself by doing that? 
Or do i just not care about that at all? Really it is down to the individual to do that otherwise why be on social media at all right? It does seem that 
most people just don't care about that because more click's on their Facebook page, Instagram, X, snapchat, that's currency in today's world. 
The more time people spend looking at my stuff rather than focusing on their own then that's better for me(or you), right?

Well that honestly and really depends what you like and level of a bridge between the real world and your online self you would like, 
most people in tech know this: it's the non-tech people that don't necessarily understand that: though it is a great deal better than it was 
10 year's ago. But back to a point I made earlier: if you or I have a monetary relationship with sites then that is not anonymous anymore and the 
only way to truly be is to just not use it. Personally I love X and the little interactions I have on there with people so Likely we be less "anonymous" 
over time as things roll out and I go deeper into the tech world, but the key point's are to clean your browser as often as is not to much of a inconvenience. 
Automating that process helps by just having the browser do it for you: plus there are new browsers like "brave" that while they have a small amount of the 
market are actually very good at helping you do this in a simple way. Mostly it is important to think about your needs as a user: be you technically 
astute with computers or not and then develop healthy habits for not just your browser: but all web activity. 

